result.execSummary:
The defendant James L. Olson was found guilty of the following charge(s) in this case.

  • Failure to Support Child (120 Days+), a class I felony, Wisconsin Statutes 948.22(2).

Charge(s) in this case were read in to this or other case(s). A "read in" charge is a charge that is dismissed as part of a plea agreement, however:

  • The defendant agrees to have the court consider the charge(s) when sentencing for another crime, under Wis. Stats. 973.20(1g)(b); and
  • The defendant cannot be prosecuted for these charge(s) in the future.

Notice to employers: It may be a violation of state law to discriminate against a job applicant because of an arrest or conviction record. Generally speaking, an employer may refuse to hire an applicant on the basis of a conviction only if the circumstances of the conviction substantially relate to the particular job. For more information, see Wisconsin Statute 111.335 and the Department of Workforce Development's publication, Arrest and Conviction Records under the Law.

supervisions.notes:
Conditional jail time to be imposed in the following manner: The jail sentence will be divided into 60 day increments. On the first day of February and the first day of August throughout the pendency of the 3 year probation term the defendant must make a payment of $2000 to be applied to child support arrears. These payments would be made in addition to the regular monthly order. Each 60 day jail sentence will be associated with a $2000 payment. If the payment is made in full and in a timely manner the 60 day jail sentence associated with it will be permanently stayed. If the payment is not made in full or in a timely manner the 60 day jail sentence is to be immediately imposed. The defendant is entitled to huber privileges. No good time credit.
Consecutive to: Any existing sentence.

miscConds.notes: Costs to be paid directly to the Waushara County Clerk of Court within 60 days or establish a payment plan.  Failure to pay may result in suspension of your driver's license, tax intercept, a civil judgment being entered against you, a warrant being issued for your arrest for contempt and/or the debt being turned over to a collection agency.

Defendant to maintain timely, uninterrupted payments as ordered in Waushara Co Case Nos. 96FA29 & 04PA7. Orders subject to modification in the future by further order of the Court. All payments are to be paid through the Wisconsin Support Collections Trust Fund (WISCTF), not through the Department of Corrections.
Defendant to comply with any further terms or conditions as deemed appropriate by the supervising agent.  DNA sample to be provided and surcharge assessed.
